.916 \\mathbf{0.916} 0.038 \\mathbf{0.038} 0.946 \\mathbf{0.946} 1.01 \\mathbf{1.01} TABLE V: Consolidated operating points for the injection-op, \n151\tstep-window, steering-site, and method ablations (small-music, fp32; n = 36 n{=}36 clips per point, 12 12 prompts × 3 \\times\\,3 seeds). Δ \\Delta w2t is the wav2taste target shift vs. the matched α \n152\t= 0 \\alpha{=}0 baseline; Δ \\Delta CLAP is the independent semantic check ( bold once it has flipped negative, i.e. off the genuine window); FAD is degradation vs. baseline. The four groups are read \n153\tin the steering results (Section IV-C ). Axis Method / site Op-point Δ \\Delta w2t Δ \\Delta CLAP FAD Injection op (DiT residual) sour additive α = 0.1 \\alpha{=}0.1 + 0.419 +0.419 + 1.77 +1.77 561 \n154\t561 additive α = 0.15 \\alpha{=}0.15 + 0.522 +0.522 − 0.63 \\mathbf{-0.63} 985 985 projection β = 1 \\beta{=}1 + 0.492 +0.492 + 0.60 +0.60 544 544 sweet additive α = 0.3 \\alpha{=}0.3 + 0.119 +0.119 \n155\t+ 2.11 +2.11 515 515 Denoise-step window (DiT residual, sour) sour early (steps 0–3) α = 0.2 \\alpha{=}0.2 + 0.530 +0.530 − 4.26 \\mathbf{-4.26} 1294 1294 late (steps 4–7) α = 0.2 \\alpha{=}0.2 \n156\t+ 0.515 +0.515 + 0.80 +0.80 565 565 Steering site sour latent (256-D) scale 1 1 + 0.385 +0.385 + 1.34 +1.34 365 365 sweet latent (256-D) scale 0.5 0.5 + 0.050 +0.050 + 0.69 +0.69 197 197 sour text \n157\t(768-D) scale 0.5 0.5 + 0.299 +0.299 − 3.04 \\mathbf{-3.04} 935 935 Method: LoRA vs. best steering sour LoRA α = 1.0 \\alpha{=}1.0 + 0.341 +0.341 − 0.92 \\mathbf{-0.92} 767 767 sweet LoRA α = 0.5 \n158\t\\alpha{=}0.5 + 0.032 +0.032 − 0.10 \\mathbf{-0.10} 171 171 sour steering proj. β = 1 \\beta{=}1 + 0.492 +0.492 + 0.60 +0.60 544 544 sweet steering add. α = 0.3 \\alpha{=}0.3 + 0.119 +0.119 + 2.11 \n159\t+2.11 515 515 IV-A Experimental setup All conditions use 10 10 s clips, loudness-normalized to − 14 -14 LUFS before scoring, with three seeds { 0 , 1 , 2 } \\{0,1,2\\} and means reported. Steering \n160\tstrength α \\alpha is expressed in units of the patched block’s mean residual norm (Section III ). Directions are grounded in norm-sonic-seasoning [ 32 ] ( 377 377 human-rated clips). We steer two \n161\treleased configurations: small-music (fp32, 20 20 blocks, d model = 1024 d_{\\text{model}}{=}1024 ) and medium (fp16, 24 24 blocks, d model = 1536 d_{\\text{model}}{=}1536 ). Medium in fp32 exceeds the \n162\t8 8 GB reference GPU. Precision therefore differs with size. To keep the two apart, we re-run small-music in both fp32 and fp16 (Section IV-B ). The two dose–responses coincide ( r = 1.00 r{=}1.00 \n163\t), which isolates the medium–small differences as scale rather than precision. Per-point significance is assessed with a two-sided Wilcoxon signed-rank test on the n = 36 n{=}36 paired deltas, \n164\tHolm-corrected across the five axes. Extraction source and layer scan We compare prompt- vs. audio-side directions by dose-response monotonicity (Spearman ρ \\rho ) and over-steer robustness, holding \n165\tblock, grid, and seeds fixed. To localize where taste is steerable, a logistic probe identifies the layers at which the axes are linearly separable. We then steer every DiT block at α = 0.15 \n166\t\\alpha=0.15 ( 5 5 prompts × 3 \\times\\,3 seeds). Blocks are ranked by the target metric alone. One candidate block per axis is then submitted to the oracle panel for confirmation or rejection. Dense \n167\twindow and oracle panel At each axis’s best layer on small-music we sweep α ∈ { 0.1 , 0.15 , 0.2 , 0.3 , 0.5 , 0.7 , 1.0 } \\alpha\\in\\{0.1,0.15,0.2,0.3,0.5,0.7,1.0\\} over 12 12 prompts × 3 \n168\t\\times\\,3 seeds, scoring every clip with the four-oracle panel of Section III (wav2taste target, CLAP cross-check, FAD, drift). A model-size study repeats the sweet sweep on medium, with each model \n169\tevaluated at its own re-scanned best layer. Ablation designs Three ablation families reuse the dense-window panel on small-music. Injection op : besides additive steering we test projection, \n170\tamplifying ( β > 0 \\beta{>}0 ) or removing ( β < 0 \\beta{<}0 ) the direction component already present per token, swept both ways. Step window : injection confined to the early ( 0 – 3 3 ) vs. \n171\tlate ( 4 4 – 7 7 ) denoise steps at matched strength. Steering site : the same difference-in-means recipe applied to the compact audio latent and the pooled text embedding, comparing residual, \n172\tlatent, and text injection. The training comparator is the per-axis rank- 8 8 LoRA of Section III ( 800 800 steps), dose-swept and scored with the same panel. aria reproduction and efficiency To \n173\tconfirm the runtime preserves steering behaviour, we re-run the dense window through aria with the identical exported direction vectors and α \\alpha grid, and report per-axis Pearson r r and MAE \n174\tagainst the SA3/PyTorch reference on the wav2taste and CLAP dose-responses. Efficiency is measured on the RTX 3070 and a CPU-only x86 tier under the warm / invocation / cold protocol of Section III-A \n175\t(Table I ). The baseline is the official Stable Audio 3 implementation (commit dedace19 , 2026-07-01; torch 2.7.1 2.7.1 , CUDA 12.6), run in half precision with its native 8 8 -step sampler and no \n176\tclassifier-free guidance. With the faster attention kernel unavailable, the repository’s fallback attention path is active, and reported memory is the process’s GPU footprint. The repository \n177\tdisables several standard performance options by default; we measured both that default and a tuned configuration (those options enabled, plus compiling the transformer) and cite the faster one \n178\tthroughout. Quantization fidelity We characterize each precision against fp16 rather than fixing a fidelity budget. Every clip is generated on the GPU with the decoder held at half precision, so a \n179\tcomparison isolates the transformer’s weight (q8, q4) or weight-plus-activation (W8A8) quantization from any device effect. We use 24 24 genre-diverse music prompts × 3 \\times\\,3 seeds ( 72 72 \n180\tclips per precision, 10 10 s, loudness-normalized). We score three metrics drawn from two independent audio models. Two come from CLAP [ 7 ] , a text–audio embedding model: prompt adherence (how \n181\tclosely each clip matches its own text prompt) and distributional quality (Fréchet Audio Distance, FAD [ 19 ] , between the precision’s clips and the fp16 set in a 32 32 -dimensional embedding \n182\tspace, reduced for stability at this sample size). The third, from the separate wav2taste [ 33 ] model, is taste preservation (the distance between the 5 5 -D taste vectors of each clip and its fp16 \n183\tcounterpart). Re-seeding fp16 (seeds 3 3 – 5 5 ) gives each metric a reference-noise floor, the change a re-seed alone induces; a precision is within noise below it. IV-B Runtime benchmarks Table I \n184\treports the three deployment regimes across both tiers. In the warm setting, with the model resident on both sides, aria slightly edges the official implementation after a round of kernel tuning and \n185\trequest reuse. A steered 10 10 s clip runs in 0.13 0.13 vs. 0.146 0.146 s (small-music) and 0.37 0.37 vs. 0.443 0.443 s (medium). It cold-starts 7.2 7.2 – 7.7 × 7.7\\times faster and holds a 1.4 \n186\t1.4 – 1.7 × 1.7\\times smaller peak GPU-memory footprint (Table I ), and its resident batch mode amortizes per-process setup to 0.60 0.60 s per job. The runtime also operates without a GPU. After a \n187\tpass that parallelizes and vectorizes the elementwise work between the matrix multiplies, a 10 10 s clip decodes in 2.5 2.5 s on small-music ( ∼ 4 × {\\sim}4\\times real time) and 9.8 9.8 s on \n188\tmedium on a 20 20 -thread CPU, and chunked sliding-window generation streams at a real-time factor of 0.6 0.6 – 4 × 4\\times on the RTX 3070. A calibrated fast preset (six denoising steps instead \n189\tof eight) trims a further ∼ 25 % {\\sim}25\\% off every transformer-bound path, with a taste-shift below the seed-to-seed noise floor on both tiers. At 60 60 s on GPU the picture inverts on the \n190\tmedium tier. A half-precision attention output stage and running the mapping convolution as a matrix multiply put aria at 1.28 1.28 s against the reference’s fused-attention path at 1.38 1.38 s, \n191\tfaster at equal precision. An opt-in 8 8 -bit-arithmetic mode (W8A8, of 4 4 -bit-class fidelity) extends the lead to 1.12 1.12 s. Only on small-music, where self-attention dominates the smaller \n192\tautoencoder, does the official path stay ahead ( 0.52 0.52 vs. 0.38 0.38 s, 1.37 × 1.37\\times ). CPU favours aria too: its banded decoder renders 60 60 s of medium 1.68 × 1.68\\times faster ( 48.0 \n193\t48.0 vs. 80.65 80.65 s), and the small-tier CPU gap to the PyTorch baseline essentially closes ( 1.09 × 1.09\\times ). The official warm figure relies on the reference’s kernel compiler, which \n194\trecompiles for each new clip length (a 14.5 14.5 – 48.1 48.1 s penalty, poorly suited to varying lengths); its medium loader also briefly needs ∼ 7.1 {\\sim}7.1 GB, overflowing an 8 8 GB card, so \n195\tthe benchmark used a low-memory load path. Quantization is close to free at 8-bit, and enables the edge Precision is a deployment axis, so we characterize rather than fix it (Table II , Figure 4 ) \n196\twith the three checks of Section IV-A . To avoid validating quantization with the same oracle the steering study optimizes, we lead with the two msclap-based metrics that share no training path with \n197\tthe taste oracle: prompt adherence and FAD. We keep the network-independent wav2taste L2 as a narrow corroborator, and scale each metric by the change a fp16 re-seed induces. Eight-bit shows no \n198\tmeasurable degradation on any of the three. Both q8 and W8A8 stay inside every re-seed floor while cutting GPU memory ∼ 21 % {\\sim}21\\% and Pi resident memory 2.3 × 2.3\\times , and W8A8 is the \n199\tfastest GPU mode ( 0.10 0.10 s warm, on the GPU’s integer tensor cores). Four-bit measurably crosses every floor, most on prompt adherence ( 5 × 5\\times its floor). It nonetheless lets the 1.2 1.2 \n200\tB medium model run on the 8 8 GB Pi ( ∼ 200 {\\sim}200 s); fidelity here is small-music, and the medium case is a memory-fit result. fp16 reproduces the fp32 dose–response ( r = 1.00 r{=}1.00 , \n201\tMAE 0.003 0.003 ; steering sweep), so precision is not confounded with the model-scale results below. Live steering Because steering runs inside the graph and the model stays warm, the control can be \n202\tturned on during a stream. With the sweet scale ramped 0 → 0.5 → 0 0{\\to}0.5{\\to}0 across a 12-chunk stream, the per-chunk taste score tracks the schedule (Spearman ρ = 0.78 \\rho{=}0.78 , p = \n203\t0.003 p{=}0.003 ), lagging on the descent as the continuation inherits context. On the Raspberry Pi 5, a steered clip costs the same as an unsteered one ( 32.9 32.9 vs. 32.8 32.8 s), so semantic \n204\tcontrol remains fully on-device. IV-C Steering results Extraction source. On small-music, the prompt-derived sweet direction yields an inverted-U response, peaking at Δ w2t = + 0.05 \n205\t\\Delta_{\\text{w2t}}{=}{+}0.05 ( α = 0.1 \\alpha{=}0.1 ) then collapsing to − 0.08 -0.08 at α = 0.2 \\alpha{=}0.2 ; the audio-derived direction reaches the same peak but remains monotonic (Spearman \n206\tρ = + 0.94 \\rho{=}{+}0.94 ) and still positive at α = 0.2 \\alpha{=}0.2 . We therefore use audio-side directions throughout. A narrow clean window The central result is that wav2taste alone is not a \n207\treliable guide. Sweeping α \\alpha at the sour axis’s best layer L19 (Figure 2 , Table III ), the oracles agree only at low strength. At α = 0.1 \\alpha{=}0.1 the shift is large ( Δ w2t = + 0.42 \n208\t\\Delta_{\\text{w2t}}{=}{+}0.42 , p = 2.9 × 10 − 11 p{=}2.9{\\times}10^{-11} , d = 3.71 d{=}3.71 ) with CLAP positive, genuine steering. Past α = 0.1 \\alpha{=}0.1 they diverge: wav2taste keeps \n209\tclimbing to its maximum at α = 0.15 \\alpha{=}0.15 while CLAP flips negative and FAD jumps. By α = 1.0 \\alpha{=}1.0 the audio has collapsed into noise-like output that wav2taste, weakest on sour ( r \n210\t≈ 0.59 r{\\approx}0.59 ), misreads as intense taste. The metric’s maximum lies inside the degradation regime. In the clean window, sweet , sour , and bitter steer genuinely with CLAP confirmation, \n211\twhereas salty and spicy stay weak even when clean; we therefore claim usable control only for the first three axes and report the case study as a bounded proof of concept, not broad taste \n212\tcontrollability. On ten held-out prompts never used for layer or strength selection, both operating points replicate ( sweet + 0.164 +0.164 , sour + 0.508 +0.508 ; Holm p = 3.7 × 10 − 9 \n213\tp{=}3.7{\\times}10^{-9} ). An audio -anchored CLAP variant (similarity to the centroid of the top-taste clips instead of a text anchor) reproduces the same boundary ( sour + 0.12 +0.12 at α = 0.1 \n214\t\\alpha{=}0.1 , negative from α = 0.3 \\alpha{=}0.3 ). The window is therefore neither a layer-selection artefact nor a text-anchoring artefact. Layer selection depends on the attribute Linear \n215\tseparability does not imply steerability. A logistic probe places taste in early text-encoding layers. Yet steering each block at α = 0.15 \\alpha{=}0.15 (Figure 3 ) shows sweet peaks mid-late at L16 \n216\tand collapses at the final blocks, while the intense tastes rank the final block first. Independent quality checks overturn that ranking: the scan-winning values already sit in the degradation regime \n217\twith CLAP negative, so layer selection cannot be delegated to the target. The most reliable operating point is sweet at L16, a modest Δ w2t = + 0.119 \\Delta_{\\text{w2t}}{=}{+}0.119 at α = 0.3 \n218\t\\alpha{=}0.3 ( p = 3.2 × 10 − 9 p{=}3.2{\\times}10^{-9} , d = 1.20 d{=}1.20 ) with CLAP + 2.11 +2.11 at bounded FAD (Table III ). Model scale A larger backbone widens the clean operating window \n219\trather than merely inflating the target metric. For sweet , medium reaches a higher clean peak ( Δ w2t = + 0.143 \\Delta_{\\text{w2t}}{=}{+}0.143 at α = 0.15 \\alpha{=}0.15 ; p = 8.9 × 10 − 9 \n220\tp{=}8.9{\\times}10^{-9} , d = 1.32 d{=}1.32 ) and holds a positive CLAP plateau farther out than small-music. At α = 0.1 \\alpha{=}0.1 medium also degrades far less on the intense tastes (lower FAD \n221\tacross axes) while keeping CLAP positive. Re-running the small model’s full window in fp16 reproduces its fp32 dose–response (pooled r = 1.00 r{=}1.00 , MAE 0.003 0.003 over all five axes), so \n222\tthe medium–small differences are scale, not precision. aria reproduces the dose–response Re-running the dense window through aria reproduces the reference closely (Table IV ): pooled wav2taste r \n223\t= 0.95 r{=}0.95 (small) and 0.92 0.92 (medium), with sweet tightest. CLAP agrees on medium ( r = 0.95 r{=}0.95 ) but is looser on small ( r = 0.86 r{=}0.86 ), reflecting a numerical offset (aria runs \n224\tin half precision where the small reference runs in full) that vanishes on medium. Both the genuine and degradation regimes carry over, so the case-study conclusions hold. Ablations: injection \n225\toperator and step window Two ablations run entirely through the runtime’s batch mode (the PyTorch injector supports neither), consolidated in Table V . Op : projection amplification (scaling up the \n226\tdirection already present in each token) matches additive steering’s peak sour shift at markedly lower FAD and with CLAP still positive ( β = 1 \\beta{=}1 : p = 2.9 × 10 − 11 \n227\tp{=}2.9{\\times}10^{-11} , d = 4.08 d{=}4.08 ), but it does nothing for sweet , whose residual component is too small to amplify. The two operators are complementary across axes. Steering away from \n228\tthe direction has little effect on either axis. Window : confining injection to the late denoise steps (4–7) roughly halves the damage at matched taste shift (late α = 0.2 \\alpha{=}0.2 : p = 2.9 \n229\t× 10 − 11 p{=}2.9{\\times}10^{-11} , d = 5.10 d{=}5.10 , CLAP positive, vs. the early steps’ CLAP collapse), consistent with early steps setting global structure while late steps shape the timbre \n230\tboth oracles read. Steering sites vary by attribute The same protocol evaluates the pipeline’s three injection sites (Table V ). The compact- latent site steers sour cleanly, a better \n231\tquality-per-shift point than the residual site (scale 1 1 : p = 2.9 × 10 − 11 p{=}2.9{\\times}10^{-11} , d = 3.11 d{=}3.11 , CLAP positive at low FAD), but fails sweet , which inverts. The \n232\ttext-embedding site fails both axes at every scale tested ( 0.5 0.5 – 32 32 ): even the smallest nudge reads as degradation and sweet turns negative. This suggests that a mean shift in the \n233\ttext-embedding space moves the conditioning off the data manifold rather than encoding “more taste”, and corroborates the prompt-side extraction failure at the embedding level. sour , an overtly \n234\ttimbral attribute, is steerable at latent and residual sites alike, while sweet responds only to mid-late residual injection. Steering versus LoRA Under the same evaluation panel, the trigger-token \n235\tLoRA (rank 8 8 , 800 800 steps) never reaches a CLAP-positive operating point on either axis (Table V ): sour peaks with CLAP negative, below steering’s clean shift, and sweet barely moves ( p = \n236\t0.16 p{=}0.16 , n.s.), turning negative at higher strength. A larger, longer-trained adapter (rank 32 32 , 3 × 3\\times the steps) lands in the same place. The cost comparison is one-sided too: LoRA \n237\tneeds ∼ 5 {\\sim}5 min of training, 5.15 5.15 M parameters, and 10.4 10.4 MB per axis, whereas steering trains nothing, stores a 4 4 – 6 6 KB vector, runs in-graph at no overhead, and is removable \n238\tat serve time. For this lexically ill-defined attribute, parameter updates add no control over a simple steering vector: steering wins on effect and cleanliness, not only on cost. V Discussion V-A \n239\tImplications of warm-parity edge deployment On warm throughput the two stacks are within a few percent, with aria marginally ahead: the runtime gains less from faster arithmetic than from removing \n240\tframework startup, GPU-context setup, and per-length compilation, the costs that dominate short generations. Interactive and embedded settings benefit most from a resident, warm model, since cold \n241\tstart, memory footprint, and predictable behaviour across clip lengths matter more there than steady-state speed. The one remaining GPU deficit is long-form generation on the small tier; on medium \n242\taria overtakes the official path at exact precision, and CPU-only it renders the same clip faster. Quantization is what makes the embedded tier practical: 8-bit shows no measurable degradation on any \n243\tof the three checks, releasing the full-precision copy turns lower precision into a memory reduction that reaches an 8 8 GB Pi at 4 4 -bit, and on the GPU 8-bit arithmetic is the fastest mode, so \n244\tcompression and speed do not trade off. V-B Learned oracles require independent checks When an intervention is tuned to maximize a learned metric, that metric ceases to be a faithful indicator once \n245\tthe intervention becomes too aggressive: the target keeps rising while causally independent checks collapse. The same limitation applies to layer selection, because the target can mistake degradation \n246\tfor success. Both the strength and the site of an intervention must therefore be supervised by quality signals that share no training path with the target. This caution extends to any \n247\trepresentation-editing evaluation that reports the optimized quantity as its own evidence. V-C Scope and limitations The systems contributions (the runtime, the quantization study, the efficiency \n248\tcomparison) rest on direct measurement and stand on their own. The steering study is scoped as a bounded case study. It intervenes on a single model family with learned or distributional oracles, so \n249\twe claim genuine control only for the three attributes where independent checks confirm it and treat the rest as a negative result. Those operating points replicate on held-out prompts, survive an \n250\taudio-anchored re-test, and are stable across a precision change (half versus full), the runtime port, and a stronger adapter (Section IV-C ). What remains open is perceptual confirmation, since no \n251\tautomatic oracle equals human listening. A listening study is therefore the natural next step rather than a gap in the present claims, which are pitched at exactly what the oracles can and cannot \n252\tcertify. VI Conclusion We presented aria , a dependency-free C/CUDA runtime for Stable Audio 3, to show that a state-of-the-art latent-diffusion music model can be deployed without a \n253\tdatacenter-oriented serving stack. In roughly 7.7 7.7 k lines of C, with no framework or third-party dependencies, aria runs the full text-to-music pipeline on a commodity CPU and an inexpensive GPU: \n254\tit matches the official implementation’s warm GPU throughput (slightly exceeding it after kernel tuning), cuts cold start by about 7 × 7\\times , lowers peak GPU memory, and runs CPU-only at ∼ \n255\t\\sim 4 × 4\\times real time, with long-form GPU generation on the small tier its one remaining limitation. Treating precision as a deployment axis, 8-bit weights leave prompt adherence, \n256\tdistributional quality, and taste all within re-seed noise, 8-bit arithmetic runs fastest on the GPU, and releasing the full-precision weights once compressed puts the 1.2 1.2 B model on an 8 8 GB Pi \n257\tat 4 4 -bit. Its bit-exact activation-steering interface reproduces the reference dose–response, and the sonic-seasoning case study shows that taste control is real but confined to a narrow \n258\toperating window for a subset of attributes. The wider lesson is that semantic control should be evaluated with independent quality checks, not with the optimized metric alone. VI-A Outlook Several \n259\textensions are clear. Fusing the decoder’s kernels has reversed the medium-tier long-form gap, so aria overtakes the official path there at exact precision. The remaining small-tier distance comes \n260\tfrom the transformer’s full self-attention, whose attention weights we measure to be too spread out for a banded approximation; a fused attention kernel (FlashAttention-class) behind a build flag \n261\tis the open lever. A persistent server mode would keep the model resident for multi-client serving and support latent-domain streaming continuation [ 2 ] . The main open validation is perceptual. As \n262\tfuture work we plan a human listening study, using pairwise comparisons fit with a Bradley–Terry model [ 1 ] , to externally confirm the automatic oracles on the attributes where they indicate \n263\tgenuine control. Both SA3 variants run on a Raspberry Pi 5, the medium only at 4 4 -bit, where the 8 8 -bit-arithmetic path is the fastest CPU mode. Acknowledgment This work was funded by the \n264\tEuropean Union - NextGenerationEU, under the National Recovery and Resilience Plan (PNRR). References [1] R. A. Bradley and M. E. Terry (1952) Rank analysis of incomplete block designs: i. the method \n265\tof paired comparisons . Biometrika 39 ( 3/4 ), pp. 324–345 . Cited by: § VI-A . [2] A. Caillon, B. McWilliams, C. Tarakajian, I. Simon, I. Manco, J. Engel, N. Constant, Y. Li, T. I. Denk, A. \n266\tLalama, A. Agostinelli, C. A. Huang, E. Manilow, G. Brower, H. Erdogan, H. Lei, I. Rolnick, I. Grishchenko, M. Orsini, M. Kastelic, M. Zuluaga, M. Verzetti, M. Dooley, O. Skopek, R. Ferrer, Z. \n267\tBorsos, A. van den Oord, D. Eck, E. Collins, J. M. Baldridge, T. Hume, C. Donahue, K. Han, and A. Roberts (2025) Live music models . In The Thirty-ninth Annual Conference on Neural Information \n268\tProcessing Systems Creative AI Track: Humanity , External Links: Link Cited by: § II-A , § III-A , § VI-A . [3] G. Camporese (2026-05) Mood vectors in audio diffusion: steeri